CHAPTER 6: SIMPLEX‑INSPIRED SHADOW‑MODE CERTIFICATION

6.1 The Simplex Analogy for Neuro‑Guidance

In fault‑tolerant computing, the Simplex architecture (Sha, 2001) consists of:

· A certified safety controller (baseline) that is known to be safe.
· An uncertified advanced controller (enhanced) that may provide better performance.
· A decision module (monitor) that switches to the safety controller when the advanced controller’s command would lead to unsafe behaviour.

In our framework:

· Safety controller: NPC + CBF (the CBF filter ensures safety even if the advanced controller fails).
· Advanced controller: RL policy (dual‑path Lipschitz).
· Monitor: The CBF‑QP itself (it projects unsafe commands onto the safe set).

Thus the RL policy is treated as an uncertified unit – it can be arbitrarily complex, non‑linear, and even wrong. The safety core (NPC + CBF) guarantees constraint satisfaction.

6.2 Shadow Mode Definition

In Shadow Mode, the RL policy runs onboard and its outputs are logged, but do not affect the actuators. The vehicle is controlled solely by the NPC + CBF (which is already certified). This allows accumulation of statistical evidence without any risk. Post‑flight, engineers can analyze the RL commands and compare them to the actual CBF‑filtered commands.

6.3 Incremental Certification Pathway

We propose a three‑phase certification plan:

· Phase 0 (Offline): Verify the CBF‑QP safety core using reachability analysis (Section 6.5). No verification of the RL network is required.
· Phase 1 (Shadow Mode – 1 mission): Fly with RL in shadow mode. Log all RL commands and the CBF modifications. Success criterion: In 100% of the trajectory, the CBF modification was small (e.g., |\Delta\sigma^* - \Delta\sigma_{\text{RL}}| \le 2^\circ), indicating that the RL policy rarely suggested unsafe actions. This provides statistical confidence.
· Phase 2 (Advisory Mode – 1–2 missions): RL commands are displayed to mission control (via uplink during communication windows) but not executed. Controllers can optionally enable them if confidence is high. The CBF remains active as a safety monitor.
· Phase 3 (Closed‑Loop Mode – human missions): RL commands are executed, but the CBF filter remains active. An emergency revert‑to‑NPC switch is available. The system is considered certified because the safety core is proven and the RL only improves performance.

6.4 Formal Safety Reduction

Theorem 6.1 (Certification Reduction): Under the Simplex‑inspired architecture with a CBF‑QP safety monitor that is perfectly implemented (i.e., solves the QP exactly and applies the control without delay), the overall system is safe (never violates constraints) if and only if:

1. The safety core (NPC + CBF) is safe under nominal conditions.
2. The monitor correctly computes the projection onto the safe set.

The correctness of the RL policy is irrelevant for safety.

Proof: The CBF filter modifies the RL command to satisfy \dot{h} \ge -\alpha h at every step. Forward invariance of \mathcal{C} holds regardless of the RL command (Theorem 4.1). Hence safety does not depend on the RL network. ∎

Corollary 6.1 (Delay‑Tolerant Reduction): With bounded computational delay \tau \le \tau_{\max} and a predictive CBF as in Section 4.7, the same reduction holds for a slightly contracted safe set \mathcal{C}_{\tau}.

6.5 Verification of the Safety Core (CBF)

To certify the safety core, we must verify that the CBF condition is satisfied for all reachable states. This can be done using Hamilton‑Jacobi reachability analysis on a reduced‑order model (e.g., 2‑DOF longitudinal dynamics). The HJ PDE is solved offline on a grid; the solution provides the maximal control invariant set. We then check that our CBF set \mathcal{C} is a subset of this maximal set. This verification is computationally feasible for 2‑3 state dimensions.

6.6 Handling Numerical Errors in QP

Theorem 6.1 assumes perfect QP implementation. In practice, floating‑point errors may cause the constraint to be violated by a small margin \epsilon_{\text{QP}}. We can incorporate a safety margin into the CBF:

\dot{h}(\mathbf{x}, u) \ge -\alpha h(\mathbf{x}) + \delta,

where \delta > 0 is chosen larger than the worst‑case numerical error. Then even with errors, the true constraint remains satisfied. This is standard practice in control barrier function implementations.

