Appendix F: Shadow‑Mode Certification Checklist (NASA Class A Compliance)

This appendix provides a template for certifying the Neuro‑Guidance system according to NASA software safety standards (NPR 7150.2, NASA‑STD‑8739.8). The checklist assumes that the safety core (NPC + CBF) has been verified offline.

F.1 Requirements Traceability

Requirement ID Description Verification Method Status
R1 The system shall never violate heat flux limit q \le q_{\max}. CBF proof (Theorem 4.1) + delay margin (Appendix D) Verified analytically
R2 The system shall never exceed control authority \( \sigma \le \sigma_{\max}\).
R3 The RL policy shall not cause actuator jitter exceeding 5^\circ per second. Lipschitz bound (Theorem 5.2) Verified ( L_\pi \cdot \epsilon_\rho bounded)
R4 The system shall revert to safe mode (NPC only) upon detection of CBF‑QP infeasibility. Reversion logic (Section 7.4) Design verified
R5 The system shall log RL commands in Shadow Mode for post‑flight analysis. Data logging design Implemented

F.2 Verification of Safety Core (Offline)

· Control Invariant Set Computation: Using HJ reachability on reduced 2‑DOF model, the set \mathcal{C} is shown to be control invariant under the CBF condition. (Appendix B)
· CBF Feasibility: For all \mathbf{x} in the entry corridor, the QP has a non‑empty feasible set when \Delta\sigma_{\text{RL}} = 0. (Lemma 4.1)
· Delay Robustness: With \tau_{\max} = 50 ms, the safety margin \tau_{\max} L_h is computed as 0.05 \times 2000 = 100 W/cm², which is added to the heat flux limit (i.e., q_{\max} reduced by 100). The resulting safe set is still non‑empty for nominal trajectories.
· Numerical Robustness: The QP solution is implemented in double precision; a safety margin \delta = 10^{-6} is added to the constraint to account for floating‑point errors.

F.3 Shadow Mode Acceptance Criteria

For a mission to transition from Shadow Mode to Advisory Mode, the following criteria must be met (to be checked post‑flight):

· Criterion 1: In 100% of the trajectory, the RL command \Delta\sigma_{\text{RL}} lies within the feasible interval [\Delta\sigma_{\min}, \Delta\sigma_{\max}] (i.e., the CBF filter did not need to modify the command). This indicates that the RL policy is safe under the encountered conditions.
· Criterion 2: The landing error achieved by the NPC alone is within the mission requirement (e.g., 10 km). This ensures that even if RL is never used, the mission is still successful.
· Criterion 3: No unexpected sensor faults or numerical errors caused a revert to NPC.

If these criteria are satisfied for two consecutive missions (one in Shadow, one in Advisory), the system is certified for Closed‑Loop Mode.

F.4 Emergency Revert Logic

The following conditions trigger an immediate revert to pure NPC (bypassing the RL and CBF):

1. CBF‑QP infeasibility (should not happen, but if detected, revert).
2. RL inference timeout (no output received within 10 ms).
3. EKF divergence (covariance trace exceeds threshold).
4. Manual command from ground (via uplink during communication windows).

The revert is implemented as a hardware‑level switch (redundant) to ensure fail‑safe operation.

F.5 Software Assurance Level (SAL)

The Neuro‑Guidance system is classified as SAL‑A (human‑rated) because it controls a critical function (entry guidance). The safety core (NPC + CBF) is developed according to DO‑178C Level A. The RL policy is developed as an uncertified supplement (DAL‑D or lower). The monitor (CBF‑QP) is part of the safety core and therefore Level A.

